javayang@... wrote:
&gt; Howdy folks,
&gt; 
&gt; I have a test method that iteratres through a String array performing
&gt; assert checks.  The problem I have is on the first failure, the tests
&gt; discontinues and the rest of the array is not checked.  This makes
&gt; sense because of the exception that is thrown and handled by JUNIT.
&gt; Is there a away I can keep the loop running until it finishes all the
&gt; strings.  I can catch the exception but how do I add it to the
&gt; current aggregate test results that JUNIT is keeping track of.  Also,
&gt; is this the best way or proper way to do this?  I don&#39;t think it
&gt; makes very much sense to write a test method for each string in the
&gt; arry, it wouldn&#39;t be very scalable or dynamic.  Thanks in advance for
&gt; any help or advice. 

I think you could write a test *suite* for this. Perhaps something along
the lines of

 public class FooTest extends TestCase {

   public FooTest(int testValue) {
     this.testValue = testValue;
   }

   public void testBar() {
     assertEquals(..., myFoo.bar(testValue));
   }

   public static Test suite() {
     TestSuite suite = new TestSuite();
     for ...
       suite.addTest(new FooTest(i));
     }
     return suite;
   }
  }

